In marketing, psychology, and content creation, these are often called “visual earworms”, visual hooks, or optical earworms—elements engineered to create that same involuntary replay and craving. They exploit the brain’s reward system for dopamine (the “wanting” chemical), making you seek more exposure, shares, or purchases.
Why “Eye Wigs” = Dopamine-Inducing Visuals
Earworms thrive on repetition, simplicity, surprise, and emotional charge → dopamine spikes from the pleasure of recognition and anticipation.
Visual earworms do the same optically: bright/vibrant colors, bold contrasts, unexpected patterns, motion illusions, or hyper-memorable icons trigger quick dopamine bursts → you feel a mini “reward” just by looking, then crave more (scrolling, saving, buying).
